00:01:52.195 --> 00:01:55.360
Bit of an open-ended
question to kick this off,

00:01:55.360 --> 00:01:58.300
how did you get
to where you are?

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:00.670
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Gosh.

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:04.690
All I can say for sure is
there was never much of a plan.

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:08.289
I've always sort of
fallen into doing things.

00:02:08.289 --> 00:02:11.830
I mean, I learnt to cook
as a kid with my mom.

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:15.850
I was one of those restless kids
who always needed entertaining.

00:02:15.850 --> 00:02:17.680
And if it was
raining outside, I'd

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.620
be tugging at my mom's
skirt saying, what can I do?

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:21.910
I'm bored.

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:24.000
And I think when I was
four or five years old,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.130
she just propped me up
on a chair in the kitchen

00:02:27.130 --> 00:02:28.310
and got me cooking.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.204
And the first thing,
I say cooking.

00:02:31.204 --> 00:02:32.620
I mean, I think
she produced a bag

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:34.660
of icing sugar,
some green coloring,

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:37.930
and some peppermint
essence and showed me

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:41.470
how to make peppermint
creams, which is basically

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:45.367
green, edible,
mint-flavored Play-Doh.

00:02:45.367 --> 00:02:47.200
MARIANA SARACENI:
Organic, of course, right?

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:49.283
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
I doubt it very much.

00:02:49.283 --> 00:02:51.700
We're talking kind of 1969 here.

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:54.670
And my mom was a keen
cook, but organic food

00:02:54.670 --> 00:03:00.400
was a distant and not very
well-understood thing.

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:02.980
But I cottoned on pretty fast.

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.980
And in fact, I just learnt
I love loved cooking from

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:06.480
as a kid.

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:09.470
And I had with that
little introduction,

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:11.500
that little sugary
introduction to cooking,

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:14.350
I was very keen on making
cakes and desserts.

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:18.340
And I became the pastry chef for
my mom's '70s dinner parties.

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:23.200
And I learned to make
things like pineapple mousse

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:27.610
and profiteroles and
chocolate roulades and things

00:03:27.610 --> 00:03:30.040
like that, some
of which still get

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:32.687
knocked up from time to time
on special occasions today.

00:03:32.687 --> 00:03:34.270
MARIANA SARACENI:
One of my colleagues

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:37.750
actually, when I told
her that you were coming,

00:03:37.750 --> 00:03:41.507
she immediately said, he has
the best meringue recipe.

00:03:41.507 --> 00:03:42.840
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL: Ah.

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:43.339
Good.

00:03:43.339 --> 00:03:45.384
That's very pleasing to hear.

00:03:45.384 --> 00:03:47.550
Hopefully, we'll get on to
vegetables at some point.

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:48.023
MARIANA SARACENI: I know.

00:03:48.023 --> 00:03:48.524
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:48.524 --> 00:03:49.939
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Yeah.

00:03:49.939 --> 00:03:52.850
But I mean, those things, those
little treats are important,

00:03:52.850 --> 00:03:53.350
too.

00:03:53.350 --> 00:03:54.310
MARIANA SARACENI: When
she said that, I'm like,

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:55.340
he makes desserts?

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:57.046
I actually was a bit confused.

00:03:57.046 --> 00:03:57.840
I didn't know that.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:00.250
Because, to be fair, full
disclosure here for everybody,

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:03.100
I moved here in 2007 that
I was telling you before.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:05.590
And it's when the "Fish
Fight" show was going on.

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:08.980
And I quite appreciated-- not
being from here, all the fishes

00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:11.840
that I eat are obscure because
they're not in our language.

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:14.020
So it was quite easy
to go to a fishmonger

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:16.029
and just show up and
be like, I want that.

00:04:16.029 --> 00:04:19.329
So between then, and now
your fight for vegetables,

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:21.430
reducing wastage,
everything, you clearly

00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:26.110
are one of the heroes or the
pioneers of the good food

00:04:26.110 --> 00:04:28.060
movement.

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:30.395
What happened in your
life, in your family,

00:04:30.395 --> 00:04:32.020
in your eating habits
that actually you

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:34.640
decided, you know what, we
you do something about this?

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:36.806
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
That's a good question.

00:04:36.806 --> 00:04:39.940
And moving on from my
sweet-toothed youth,

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:42.970
I never really planned
to become a chef.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:44.920
I've been cooking
all my life, and I

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:48.670
enjoyed cooking at university
and with my friends.

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:52.480
But my plan after
I left university,

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:54.840
I was really interested
in wildlife conservation,

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:56.590
and I planned a trip
and a friend of mine.

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:59.350
And we went to southern
Africa for six months.

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:02.125
We hired a pickup truck.

00:05:02.125 --> 00:05:04.000
We bought a pickup truck,
which we sold again

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:04.958
at the end of the trip.

00:05:04.958 --> 00:05:08.290
And we drove away camping a
lot, visiting game reserves.

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:10.540
We took a tape recorder with
us and interviewed people

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:13.210
working in the world
of conservation.

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:17.230
And I came back to the UK
hungry to do more of that

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:20.500
and looking for a way
to get back to Africa,

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:23.740
maybe trying to come
up with a book idea.

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:25.620
But while I was doing
that, a friend of mine

00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:28.320
was working as a waitress
at the River Cafe--

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:30.735
now celebrating this year
its 30th anniversary--

00:05:30.735 --> 00:05:35.040
a wonderful pioneering
West London restaurant

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.620
run by two amazing women,
as I'm sure many of you

00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:41.580
know, Ruthie Rogers and
Rose Gray, Rose very sadly

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:43.050
no longer with us.

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:48.090
But I walked in one day looking
for a job in the kitchen

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:49.227
or as a waiter, whatever.

00:05:49.227 --> 00:05:51.060
And someone in the
kitchen hadn't turned up,

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:54.990
and they asked me if my
would stand at the pass

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:57.030
and help dress some
salads as they went out.

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:59.130
And after the lunch service
where I didn't totally

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:01.620
disgrace myself, they said
what do you like to do?

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.540
I said, I like making puddings.

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:06.210
So they asked me, they said,
can you make a lemon tart?

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:09.460
So as it happened, I had a
lemon tart recipe up my sleeve.

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:14.250
So I made a lemon tart, and
they said, that's not bad,

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:16.350
and we'll put that
on the menu tonight.

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:18.240
It's not how we make ours.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:20.550
We can do that if you want
to come back tomorrow.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:23.700
So I did come back
tomorrow, and I ended up

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:25.950
doing six months
at the River Cafe.

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:29.125
And I won't say I never
made it back to Africa

00:06:29.125 --> 00:06:30.750
because I had made
it back a few times,

00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:34.380
but that was the switch point.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:37.560
But there was something about
that fascination with wildlife

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:39.540
and the wider
story of the planet

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:42.450
that I think has always
informed my interest in food

00:06:42.450 --> 00:06:46.400
and has also allowed me
in a very lucky way--

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:48.240
because the TV work
that I've done--

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:52.310
it's allowed me to come back and
look at the conservation stroke

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:56.680
sustainability issues in
the business of global food.

00:06:56.680 --> 00:06:58.860
And I mean not just global
food, but what we all

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:01.980
choose to eat every day
is part of that story.

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.270
What we are choosing
to eat on a daily basis

00:07:04.270 --> 00:07:07.950
is probably affecting the planet
more than any other decisions

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:09.510
being made by human beings.

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:12.407
I mean, we do extremely
things on this planet.

00:07:12.407 --> 00:07:13.740
We make extraordinary buildings.

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:17.400
We build amazing
electronic gadgetry

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:20.940
and we program it in
brilliant and innovative ways.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.900
And that, of course,
affects the world,

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:25.650
but probably nothing
affects the world more

00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:27.600
than the way we produce food.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:31.440
It's the main reason we're
chopping down forests,

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:35.364
which arguably-- well, in
my view, not arguably--

00:07:35.364 --> 00:07:36.030
we need to keep.

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:38.250
We're doing all
sorts of things often

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:42.090
in the name of feeding the
world that could ultimately

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:44.280
jeopardize feeding the world.

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:47.490
Because, if we don't look after
the primary resources of--

00:07:47.490 --> 00:07:49.410
I'm going off on
one now, aren't I--

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:51.060
the primary resources
of a planet.

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:51.600
MARIANA SARACENI: I want
to be like, stop it.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:52.279
Everybody, veg.

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:54.070
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Well, exactly.

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:56.760
I mean, if we don't look
after those primary resources

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:00.280
in a sustainable way, we will
run out of stuff to grow food

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:01.710
on and we'll be in trouble.

00:08:06.750 --> 00:08:08.610
But the great thing,
the exciting thing,

00:08:08.610 --> 00:08:12.660
is that we can cook and eat
our way out of this problem

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:17.040
by changing the decisions
and the choices that we make.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:18.900
Many, many things are
happening in the world

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:21.810
that make those changes
really, really hard.

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:24.480
We are hugely
under the influence

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:26.910
of the industrial
food machine, and it

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:28.950
wants us to behave
in certain ways

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:32.159
because it's highly
profitable if we do.

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:34.404
And what it's become
incredibly good at--

00:08:34.404 --> 00:08:35.820
I really am going
off on one now--

00:08:35.820 --> 00:08:40.620
what it's become incredibly good
is molding very inexpensive,

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:43.860
highly-subsidized,
highly-refined ingredients,

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:49.680
essentially sugar, cheap
vegetable and animal fats,

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:52.170
and highly-refined starches--

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:55.560
wheat flour is a lot
of it, but increasingly

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:57.980
soya starch and
things like that--

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:01.200
just respinning them into
endless different products

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:03.660
and putting little bits
and sprinkles on that

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:07.320
actually make them incredibly
difficult to resist.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:09.060
It's pretty much
an exact science

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:12.300
making inexpensive food
very hard to resist

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:14.490
and creaming off
a lot of profit.

00:09:14.490 --> 00:09:17.760
And that's taking us
away from the sort

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:19.830
of bounty of natural
foods that really

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:22.590
should underpin our diet.

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:25.710
And essentially, that's
unrefined plant foods.

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:30.060
That's what we need to put back
at the center of our eating.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:34.380
Doesn't mean we have to
be vegetarian or vegan.

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:36.300
I'm neither of those things.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:37.770
I eat meat and fish.

00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:41.540
But I eat meat and
fish carefully, I hope.

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:45.810
And to eat any of those
things without thought

00:09:45.810 --> 00:09:48.300
is potentially contributing
to the problem.

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:50.340
To make your food choices
in a thoughtful way

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:51.885
is contributing to the solution.

00:09:51.885 --> 00:09:53.260
MARIANA SARACENI:
That's actually

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:56.610
a perfect opening to my next
question because I've been--

00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:58.805
Netflix, there's five
million food documentaries,

00:09:58.805 --> 00:10:01.434
and I just love watching
everything food related.

00:10:01.434 --> 00:10:02.850
And I've been
watching quite a lot

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:05.880
of vegan and plant-based
documentaries.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:08.880
And both views tend to
be very black and white.

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:11.680
Either you eat meat or
you never eat meat at all.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:14.820
One of them actually was
the most generous one saying

00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:15.965
it will not be sustainable.

00:10:15.965 --> 00:10:17.340
If the entire
planet wants to eat

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:20.610
organic plant-based food 100%,
it will not be sustainable.

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:22.880
You do not have
to be 100% vegan.

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:25.630
You just need to be very
mindful of what you eat.

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:27.340
I was just telling
you before I currently

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:30.390
have in my diet two
vegetarian days a week,

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:32.770
and I'm trying to incorporate
a vegan one, which I really

00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:34.395
hope you help me
because I'm struggling

00:10:34.395 --> 00:10:36.340
without the cheese
and the butter.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:38.110
But how do you think
we should approach

00:10:38.110 --> 00:10:39.330
this in terms of quantities?

00:10:39.330 --> 00:10:42.640
Not only having the animals as a
side dish rather than the main,

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:45.230
how do you think people
should approach this?

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:45.340
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
I think

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:47.380
there are many different
ways to approach it.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:49.540
And I mean, it is
interesting to me

00:10:49.540 --> 00:10:51.910
that more and more
people and young people

00:10:51.910 --> 00:10:54.357
are making the
choice to be vegan.

00:10:54.357 --> 00:10:55.690
And I think it's a great choice.

00:10:55.690 --> 00:10:58.690
I mean, because I've written
enthusiastically about meats--

00:10:58.690 --> 00:11:02.770
one of my early books was
"The River Cottage Meat Book,"

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:06.190
and I've cooked meat
and fish in the shows--

00:11:09.459 --> 00:11:11.500
other chefs have put
themselves out there somehow

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:14.500
being critical of
vegetarianism or veganism.

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:19.370
And maybe sometimes people have
assumed that I'm in that camp.

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:21.670
I think it's great that more
and more young people are

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:22.630
choosing to be vegan.

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:25.630
I've got time for anyone
with principles about food.

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:28.030
Anybody who's thinking
about what they eat

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:30.190
and thinking about the
consequences of the choices

00:11:30.190 --> 00:11:34.120
they're making, I
think that's fantastic.

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:38.290
And if more and more
people on the planet

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:39.880
become vegan and
vegetarian, that's

00:11:39.880 --> 00:11:42.220
going to help the situation.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:44.860
I do think there are
ways to incorporate

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:46.480
fish and meat into your diet.

00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:49.300
I think both foods can be
very healthy if well-chosen.

00:11:49.300 --> 00:11:51.820
And they can be sustainable--
again, if carefully chosen.

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:55.060
But the thing that's really
difficult and damaging

00:11:55.060 --> 00:11:58.390
is this idea that was
born of the great miracle

00:11:58.390 --> 00:12:01.870
of industrial farming of
industrial meat production,

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:05.410
that somehow no meal is
complete without meat--

00:12:05.410 --> 00:12:09.775
somehow, two or even
three times a day.

00:12:09.775 --> 00:12:12.940
The old, great,
British breakfast fry

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:18.502
up once in a while, twice a
year maybe, fantastic thing.

00:12:18.502 --> 00:12:19.960
But I mean, if
you're going to have

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:25.300
sausages and bacon for breakfast
and a beef sandwich at lunch

00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:27.280
and then more meat or
fish in the evening,

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:30.310
if we're all doing that,
there's no way we're not

00:12:30.310 --> 00:12:31.960
in trouble as a planet.

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:34.100
So we've really got
to balance things out.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:37.690
And I think meat and fish
can be incredibly delicious.

00:12:37.690 --> 00:12:42.070
If you put a little bit
of fierce heat on them

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:44.110
and you sear that
edge of the steak

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:45.700
or the crispy skin
or the fish, you

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:47.080
create a really special flavor.

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:47.740
And I get that.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:49.630
And that's something
we can enjoy.

00:12:49.630 --> 00:12:52.870
And also in moderation,
those foods are very healthy.

00:12:52.870 --> 00:12:56.920
They've got great proteins
in them, good amino acids.

00:12:56.920 --> 00:12:58.930
They're good, digestible foods.

00:12:58.930 --> 00:13:02.260
So that's kind of where I'm at.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:10.000
But to recklessly consume them
the sort of commodity foods

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.737
is a big part of
the problems that

00:13:11.737 --> 00:13:14.320
are stacking up that we're going
to have to solve in the years

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:15.100
ahead.

00:13:15.100 --> 00:13:16.930
MARIANA SARACENI:
Very much agree.

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:21.720
In terms of now jumping
into vegetable specific,

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:23.020
your mother--

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:24.904
you come from a
gardener family, so you

00:13:24.904 --> 00:13:27.070
have an unfair advantage
because in my family nobody

00:13:27.070 --> 00:13:27.819
has a green thumb.

00:13:27.819 --> 00:13:30.312
So in terms of growing, I've
tried and failed miserably.

00:13:30.312 --> 00:13:32.770
I even signed up and paid for
an allotment that is just now

00:13:32.770 --> 00:13:35.080
flowers because I have no clue.

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:37.870
Do you have any tips
for us Londoners

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:41.110
living in the typical,
non-outer-space London

00:13:41.110 --> 00:13:42.550
apartment?

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:43.966
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Yeah.

00:13:43.966 --> 00:13:46.804
I mean, I think if you've
got any space at all--

00:13:46.804 --> 00:13:48.970
and it doesn't even have
to be outdoor space-- where

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:54.271
you can put a pot with soil
in it, I mean, lots of people

00:13:54.271 --> 00:13:55.270
are in the house plants.

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:56.978
I think why not grow
edible house plants.

00:13:56.978 --> 00:13:59.300
I mean, that just
makes me more excited

00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:00.850
the fact that at
the end of it I'm

00:14:00.850 --> 00:14:02.240
going to get some
food out of it.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:05.470
It might just be a window box
full of herbs or one big pot

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:09.000
with a tomato plant
growing in a sunny window.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.900
Anything like that,
anything that you've

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:13.990
grown yourself is always going
to taste fantastic and just

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:14.920
remind you--

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:17.810
not necessarily consciously,
but subliminally--

00:14:17.810 --> 00:14:21.517
that this stuff
comes from the soil.

00:14:21.517 --> 00:14:22.600
We can take a bit of soil.

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:24.183
We can look after
our own bit of soil,

00:14:24.183 --> 00:14:25.870
and we can grow
some food from it.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:30.400
And we're connected
to the whole process.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:31.870
And we're connected
to the problem.

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:33.203
We're connected to the solution.

00:14:33.203 --> 00:14:36.580
We're part of it.

00:14:36.580 --> 00:14:39.790
I mean, obviously, if you can
find an allotment in London

00:14:39.790 --> 00:14:43.770
and get a bit busy, people
get really excited about that.

00:14:43.770 --> 00:14:46.540
And once you start
doing a bit of that,

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:50.330
from the people I talk to,
people tend not to backslide.

00:14:50.330 --> 00:14:53.170
Once you start growing
a little bit of food,

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:56.200
it's a pleasure that
becomes part of your life

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:58.345
and you tend to want
to do more and more.

00:14:58.345 --> 00:14:59.980
MARIANA SARACENI: Is there
like a super-easy one, one

00:14:59.980 --> 00:15:01.190
of the vegetables or
spices you can be like,

00:15:01.190 --> 00:15:02.140
you really can't mess this up?

00:15:02.140 --> 00:15:02.470
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Well, lots of things

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:03.700
are much easier than
you think, but I

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:05.170
think the really
important thing is

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:07.990
to choose something that you
will then really look forward

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:09.029
to eating.

00:15:09.029 --> 00:15:11.320
There's no point in growing
a vegetable that you're not

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:14.410
enthusiastic about, maybe
just because it looks cool.

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:17.560
Very easy to grow
a courgette plant

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:23.380
on a balcony or a window sill.

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:26.540
A fun thing to do is to
grow things in a window box

00:15:26.540 --> 00:15:28.760
and direct them that way
and then let them climb up

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:30.800
a trellis and harvest
them on the floor above.

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:32.630
You know, there's all
sort of fun you can have.

00:15:32.630 --> 00:15:34.730
MARIANA SARACENI: Talk to
your neighbors first, please.

00:15:34.730 --> 00:15:36.896
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Climbing beans and peas

00:15:36.896 --> 00:15:37.820
are easy to grow.

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:39.680
Herbs, obviously, really
useful because you

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:42.890
can use a bit of them every
day or a few times a week.

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:45.360
Just grow something that you're
going to get excited about.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:46.526
MARIANA SARACENI: Beautiful.

00:15:46.526 --> 00:15:48.920
Besides growing, any tips
for buying vegetables

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:50.180
in the supermarket.

00:15:50.180 --> 00:15:51.790
Farmers' market I'm
hoping are ideal,

00:15:51.790 --> 00:15:54.090
but if there's no
close-by farmers'

00:15:54.090 --> 00:15:57.020
market, tips from buying
vegetables in supermarkets?

00:15:57.020 --> 00:15:58.520
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
I think

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:01.550
that the ideal when
buying any food

00:16:01.550 --> 00:16:04.310
is to know as much about
it as you possibly can,

00:16:04.310 --> 00:16:06.320
to know the story of
where it comes from.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:09.720
For me, it's that connection.

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:13.610
I've talked in the past about
the idea of a sort of continuum

00:16:13.610 --> 00:16:18.170
which I've sort of glibly called
the food acquisition continuum,

00:16:18.170 --> 00:16:20.802
or FAC for short.

00:16:20.802 --> 00:16:22.760
Which is, basically,
we're all somewhere on it.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:26.300
And at one end of it,
over here if you like,

00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:29.510
there are millions of us now
who are almost completely

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:32.900
dependent on made
food-- essentially,

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:34.040
industrially-produced food.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:36.930
Ready meals and takeaways,
that's what we eat.

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:37.584
We don't cook.

00:16:37.584 --> 00:16:39.250
We don't even buy
ingredients, and we're

00:16:39.250 --> 00:16:40.730
at this end of the scale.

00:16:40.730 --> 00:16:44.360
Right down at the other
end of the scale--

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:46.040
and there's not
many of the people

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:47.480
on the planet left doing this--

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:50.810
you've still got a
few Kalahari Bushman,

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:54.530
a few Amazonian tribes who are
essentially hunter-gatherers

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:57.020
who wake up in the morning
and the only real issue

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:59.330
is to feed themselves
and their extended family

00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:01.760
and the others in
their tribe, and they

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:05.890
have an extraordinary range
of seasonal knowledge.

00:17:05.890 --> 00:17:08.480
And as far as they may have
been left some land that they

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:14.030
can still explore, historical
and tribal and seasonal

00:17:14.030 --> 00:17:16.099
knowledge and the
different value

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:18.020
of plants at different
times of year, and they

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:19.369
may still hunt and fish.

00:17:19.369 --> 00:17:21.702
Not many of them left, as I
say, but we're all somewhere

00:17:21.702 --> 00:17:22.970
on that continuum.

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:26.300
And my whole contention, the
whole River Cottage argument,

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:29.060
if you like, from the very
beginning has been it's

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:34.130
really good to get a little bit
further down towards some kind

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:37.160
of self-sufficiency,
some closer connection

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:39.050
to the origins of your food.

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:41.300
And you can do it by,
just as we talked about,

00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:43.190
growing food in
whatever environment

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:44.300
you find yourself in.

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:46.730
But you could also do it
in the way that you shop.

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:50.030
And that means buying
less anonymous food

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:52.094
and more food where,
as you buy it,

00:17:52.094 --> 00:17:53.510
you get a little
bit of the story.

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:55.200
You get a bit of the context.

00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:58.840
So that's why farmers'
markets and all markets

00:17:58.840 --> 00:18:01.370
have got a lot going for them
because you've got somebody

00:18:01.370 --> 00:18:05.690
there who's selling with passion
something that they believe in.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:07.100
Maybe they've made
it themselves.

00:18:07.100 --> 00:18:09.260
Maybe they've grown
it themselves.

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:10.830
The idea of farmers'
market really

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:13.730
is they should only
be staffed by people

00:18:13.730 --> 00:18:16.640
who are connected
from the farm itself

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:20.060
so they can really tell
you the story of that food.

00:18:20.060 --> 00:18:22.220
I get that that's not
easy for everybody,

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:25.040
but it does make
shopping a real pleasure

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:28.880
in itself and the cooking
thereafter because you're

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:32.000
taking with you back into
your kitchen some of the story

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.090
and some of the understanding
and some of the connection

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:38.780
with that ingredient.

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:40.070
It's kind of mindful.

00:18:40.070 --> 00:18:43.144
It puts your mind in a better
place than if you're cooking

00:18:43.144 --> 00:18:45.560
sort of cling-wrapped, anonymous
food from the supermarket

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:48.290
and you couldn't even say
which country came from--

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:52.370
sometimes, if it's meat,
which animal or animals.

00:18:52.370 --> 00:18:53.730
There's so much you don't know.

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:56.810
I find it scary to be
presented with food that I

00:18:56.810 --> 00:18:59.030
don't know anything
about, and my basic rule

00:18:59.030 --> 00:19:01.215
is I don't eat it.

00:19:01.215 --> 00:19:02.840
MARIANA SARACENI:
That's a good policy.

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:05.789
And now, moving
specifically to this book,

00:19:05.789 --> 00:19:07.830
I have to say this is
going to sound very random,

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:11.240
but I already told you
about this I seriously

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:15.380
have love and respect for
you for the swaps option

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:16.220
that you put.

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:17.240
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
The swaps?

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:17.960
MARIANA SARACENI: Yes.

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:20.360
I am very much like yes, free
spirit, everything's great.

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:22.520
But when it comes to
a recipe, either I

00:19:22.520 --> 00:19:25.430
don't follow a recipe or
I follow a recipe to a t.

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:30.590
So if it says 336 milliliters
of [INTERPOSING VOICES],,

00:19:30.590 --> 00:19:32.630
I really get very if
I don't have that.

00:19:32.630 --> 00:19:34.213
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Precision

00:19:34.213 --> 00:19:35.867
is rarely vital in cookery.

00:19:35.867 --> 00:19:36.950
MARIANA SARACENI: I agree.

00:19:36.950 --> 00:19:38.117
Still, I know it's my issue.

00:19:38.117 --> 00:19:40.033
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
As a pastry chef,

00:19:40.033 --> 00:19:42.050
as a former pastry
chef-- well, not former,

00:19:42.050 --> 00:19:44.030
I still make some
nice desserts--

00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:46.760
but, yeah, if you're making
a cake, you need to be there

00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:47.700
or thereabouts.

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:49.741
But even then, there's
probably a little bit more

00:19:49.741 --> 00:19:50.930
give the most people think.

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:53.540
But for this kind of
cooking and for the kind

00:19:53.540 --> 00:19:59.570
of nice, rich, tasty assemblies
of different ingredients,

00:19:59.570 --> 00:20:02.480
you don't need precise
amounts of anything.

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:05.180
Maybe be a little bit
sharp with your seasonings.

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:06.590
Otherwise, you can relax.

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:08.720
And what I've done
in several books now

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:10.580
is I've suggested
a bunch of swaps.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:14.900
I mean, there's no reason at all
why a carrot recipe won't work

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:18.050
brilliantly with celeriac
or parsnips or another root

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:18.620
vegetable.

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:21.500
It won't be the same, but that
would be part of the joy of it.

00:20:21.500 --> 00:20:23.400
It will be exciting
and delicious.

00:20:23.400 --> 00:20:25.750
So I've suggested a few
swaps, but the idea really

00:20:25.750 --> 00:20:28.224
is make your own swaps.

00:20:28.224 --> 00:20:30.640
Do you think, well, I haven't
got that, but I've got this,

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:31.181
will it work?

00:20:31.181 --> 00:20:32.380
Of course it'll work.

00:20:32.380 --> 00:20:34.000
MARIANA SARACENI: Oddly enough,
I understand what you mean,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
and it makes sense.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:36.670
But in my crazy
mind, I kind of like

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:39.253
needed you, the person who wrote
the book, to tell me it's OK.

00:20:39.253 --> 00:20:39.804
Go ahead.

00:20:39.804 --> 00:20:40.845
I feel kind of validated.

00:20:40.845 --> 00:20:42.350
Like, OK, I'll play with it.

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:43.933
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
It is OK.

00:20:43.933 --> 00:20:45.200
It is OK.

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:45.740
Go ahead.

00:20:45.740 --> 00:20:46.980
MARIANA SARACENI: Thank you.

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:50.680
So considering this is not
your first vegetable cookbook,

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:53.969
how do you come to do recipes?

00:20:53.969 --> 00:20:55.510
Do you decide and
say, you know what?

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:58.020
Today, I'm going to
explore carrots or today

00:20:58.020 --> 00:20:59.050
I'm going to explore--

00:20:59.050 --> 00:21:00.092
I don't know-- buckwheat?

00:21:00.092 --> 00:21:01.966
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
The first thing,

00:21:01.966 --> 00:21:03.700
and I'm not too shy
about admitting this,

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:05.860
is it's a highly-collaborative
business for me,

00:21:05.860 --> 00:21:08.830
and I work very closely
with two amazing people.

00:21:08.830 --> 00:21:12.630
One of them used to be my
head chef at River Cottage,

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:14.130
the Cookery School, Gil Meller.

00:21:14.130 --> 00:21:16.210
He's just written a
beautiful cookery book

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:18.310
himself called "Gather,"
his first solo cookery

00:21:18.310 --> 00:21:20.680
book, which has rightly
won loads of awards--

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:23.500
very much in the spirit of
what we do at River Cottage,

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:25.840
foods of friends
gathered from close by.

00:21:29.080 --> 00:21:30.820
So he's my sounding
board for recipes.

00:21:30.820 --> 00:21:34.090
And I've also been working with
my food editor, Nikki Duffy,

00:21:34.090 --> 00:21:35.390
for more than 10 years.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:39.430
So Gil, Nikki, and I are a team,
and we get together regularly

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:41.590
and we brainstorm
ideas for a book.

00:21:41.590 --> 00:21:44.050
And we go away, and we
cook different things

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:45.820
and we send each other pictures.

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:48.640
And we get together
again and have tastings

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:49.720
and swap things around.

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:51.812
And that's how we do it.

00:21:51.812 --> 00:21:53.270
First couple of
books I wrote were,

00:21:53.270 --> 00:21:54.730
I literally kind
of sat in a garret

00:21:54.730 --> 00:21:58.270
and did them all on my own--

00:21:58.270 --> 00:22:01.810
the original "River Cottage
Cookbook" and the meat book.

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:04.400
But since I've been
working with Gil,

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:07.450
he's so talented it
just seems natural to me

00:22:07.450 --> 00:22:09.340
to swap ideas with him.

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:11.290
So we've got a
pretty good system,

00:22:11.290 --> 00:22:15.680
and the recipes only make it if
we all think they're damn fine.

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:20.390
And I love having them alongside
me to help make it all happen.

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:22.630
MARIANA SARACENI: Do you
guys test your recipes

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:23.370
on your families?

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:26.120
As in, kind of like, if my
mother-in-law passes a test?

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:28.180
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Yes, we do.

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:31.510
They don't stay just inside
that collaborative circle.

00:22:31.510 --> 00:22:34.780
We have various people.

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:37.630
My sister does quite a lot
of tasting and testing.

00:22:37.630 --> 00:22:41.009
Some of the team down
at River Cottage--

00:22:41.009 --> 00:22:43.300
not just the kitchen team
because it's really important

00:22:43.300 --> 00:22:47.170
that your recipes are tested by
people who are not in any way

00:22:47.170 --> 00:22:49.122
professional cooks
because professional cooks

00:22:49.122 --> 00:22:50.330
won't read the recipe anyway.

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:52.750
They'll do what they want.

00:22:52.750 --> 00:22:55.360
So yeah we have
a bunch of people

00:22:55.360 --> 00:22:56.830
who help us out with that.

00:22:56.830 --> 00:22:57.490
MARIANA SARACENI:
Including kids?

00:22:57.490 --> 00:22:59.615
Because that's another
thing, I have three nephews,

00:22:59.615 --> 00:23:01.995
and it's quite challenging to
get them to eat a vegetable

00:23:01.995 --> 00:23:04.120
unless you make a story of
the magic of the tomato.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:05.536
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Yeah.

00:23:05.536 --> 00:23:07.750
I mean, I don't
necessarily put kids

00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:09.580
in charge of recipe
testing, but I'm

00:23:09.580 --> 00:23:12.150
very happy for them
to get involved.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:15.460
And my recipes are being
tested in a family kitchen,

00:23:15.460 --> 00:23:18.910
and hopefully they are
passing the kid test

00:23:18.910 --> 00:23:19.980
at some level or other.

00:23:19.980 --> 00:23:20.980
MARIANA SARACENI: Great.

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:24.040
If you could pick one or
three favorite recipes

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:26.160
from this book, which
ones would they be?

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:30.610
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
That's so, so hard.

00:23:30.610 --> 00:23:34.430
I think what I'd like to say
about the recipes generally is

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:39.581
that what's so important that
we recognize about vegetables--

00:23:39.581 --> 00:23:41.830
and indeed, we should really
say plants because as you

00:23:41.830 --> 00:23:47.770
mentioned, of course the whole
spectrum includes fruits,

00:23:47.770 --> 00:23:51.820
seeds, spices, nuts,
grains, and pulses,

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:55.090
as well as the things that we
think of in an everyday sense

00:23:55.090 --> 00:23:57.070
as vegetables--

00:23:57.070 --> 00:23:59.290
we have to recognize there's
an extraordinary palette

00:23:59.290 --> 00:24:00.706
of different
textures and flavors.

00:24:00.706 --> 00:24:05.530
Compared to meat and fish, it's
an amazingly-rich, broad world

00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:08.070
of flavors.

00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:11.110
We're so hidebound and so
dominated by meat and fish

00:24:11.110 --> 00:24:12.850
in our diets that
we've hardly begun

00:24:12.850 --> 00:24:16.660
to scratch the surface of
the sheer possibilities,

00:24:16.660 --> 00:24:19.270
the infinite
possibilities of combining

00:24:19.270 --> 00:24:21.920
all the different plant
foods in delicious ways.

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:24.724
So the first thing
I've done in this book,

00:24:24.724 --> 00:24:26.140
even more than in
the last one, is

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:28.389
to sort of throw out the
rulebook and just try things.

00:24:28.389 --> 00:24:30.820
So there's loads of
recipes where I mix

00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:32.650
fruit and vegetables together.

00:24:32.650 --> 00:24:35.380
One of the things I'm
doing a lot at the moment

00:24:35.380 --> 00:24:37.060
is just, because
I've got tomatoes

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:40.300
in the greenhouse and plums
just coming to an end,

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:42.340
there's a tomato and
plum salad in there.

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:43.840
And just the two
different flavors--

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:45.464
I mean, they're both
fruits, obviously,

00:24:45.464 --> 00:24:47.560
even though we think of
tomatoes as vegetables--

00:24:47.560 --> 00:24:49.924
but just the tart
sweetness of one

00:24:49.924 --> 00:24:51.340
and the tart
sweetness of another,

00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:53.450
yet aromatically they're
completely different.

00:24:53.450 --> 00:24:55.660
As it happens, They go
really well together

00:24:55.660 --> 00:24:57.550
with a little bit
of aniseed herb,

00:24:57.550 --> 00:24:59.920
like a bit of basil or
torn tarragon in there.

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:02.676
You get an extraordinary
combination

00:25:02.676 --> 00:25:03.550
of different flavors.

00:25:03.550 --> 00:25:05.390
It's really exciting.

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:07.840
So there have been lots
of experiments there.

00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:09.690
And the recipes
there, I suppose--

00:25:09.690 --> 00:25:11.750
and I think, is it
on the menu today?

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:14.650
There's another roast
beetroot, plum, and tomato.

00:25:14.650 --> 00:25:16.150
MARIANA SARACENI:
Is it on the menu?

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:17.700
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
It's out there.

00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:18.460
MARIANA SARACENI: Yes, it is.

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:19.170
Go eat it, everyone.

00:25:19.170 --> 00:25:21.461
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
It takes those two flavors

00:25:21.461 --> 00:25:23.820
and intensifies them through
roasting and combines them

00:25:23.820 --> 00:25:26.390
with another thing, which
is a root vegetable.

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:29.480
And again, it's a
really beautiful, deep,

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:32.690
resonant spectrum of
flavors that you get.

00:25:32.690 --> 00:25:35.626
So really, it's been about
having fun with that.

00:25:35.626 --> 00:25:37.500
And the other thing, of
course, is technique.

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:39.708
And when I say that, I don't
mean in a difficult way.

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:44.990
When it comes to
fish, you know we've

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:47.895
got the barbecue, the
oven, the frying pan.

00:25:47.895 --> 00:25:49.520
And yet, for so long,
vegetables seemed

00:25:49.520 --> 00:25:52.080
to be either boiled
or raw in a salad.

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:55.970
Let's roast more vegetables.

00:25:55.970 --> 00:25:57.530
You'd really
challenge me to think

00:25:57.530 --> 00:26:00.090
of a vegetable that is
inappropriate at any time

00:26:00.090 --> 00:26:01.050
to roast.

00:26:01.050 --> 00:26:03.860
There's a recipe for
roast lettuce hearts

00:26:03.860 --> 00:26:05.780
in the book where,
in a hot oven,

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:08.060
you caramelize
those cut corners.

00:26:08.060 --> 00:26:09.890
Those little burn
brown bits that you

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:12.380
get on the edges of
your roast roots,

00:26:12.380 --> 00:26:13.850
you can do that
with cauliflower.

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:14.960
You can do that with broccoli.

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:16.168
You can do that with lettuce.

00:26:16.168 --> 00:26:18.140
You can do it with leeks.

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:20.260
You can do it with
all kinds of things.

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:21.170
MARIANA SARACENI: The
latest thing I'll try.

00:26:21.170 --> 00:26:22.753
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Does that

00:26:22.753 --> 00:26:25.470
let me off answering the what's
your favorite recipe question?

00:26:25.470 --> 00:26:28.220
The squash patties, which
are on the menu, that's

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:29.660
a little comfort.

00:26:29.660 --> 00:26:32.140
Again, you've made
something there,

00:26:32.140 --> 00:26:34.310
it's kind of a little
bit like a veggie burger,

00:26:34.310 --> 00:26:36.920
but you've surrounded it with
a few little seeds as well.

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:39.440
And you've got some chickpea
in there and some squash,

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:42.800
so it's got that satisfying,
slightly-carby comfort food

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:44.900
thing but with some
seeds and spices

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:46.880
just to give it a
little bit of edge.

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:50.378
And I think that's as satisfying
as any kind of fried thing.

00:26:50.378 --> 00:26:51.544
MARIANA SARACENI: Beautiful.

00:26:51.544 --> 00:26:54.650
I have a list of now kind
of like quickfire questions,

00:26:54.650 --> 00:26:57.220
which are very much
like one or the other.

00:26:57.220 --> 00:26:57.970
Don't get nervous.

00:26:57.970 --> 00:26:59.679
It's fine.

00:26:59.679 --> 00:27:01.220
Is there any vegetable
that you think

00:27:01.220 --> 00:27:03.120
isn't worth the while, one
that you think, you know what?

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:04.050
No.

00:27:04.050 --> 00:27:05.990
Or one that you just
simply don't like?

00:27:05.990 --> 00:27:07.781
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Any vegetables

00:27:07.781 --> 00:27:11.879
that are not worthwhile at all?

00:27:11.879 --> 00:27:13.170
MARIANA SARACENI: Don't be shy.

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:16.570
We all have something
we don't like.

00:27:16.570 --> 00:27:19.256
HUGH
FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL: God.

00:27:19.256 --> 00:27:21.720
I'm just trying to think.

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:23.130
AUDIENCE: Baby sweetcorn.

00:27:23.130 --> 00:27:23.670
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
What's that?

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:25.027
AUDIENCE: Baby sweetcorn

00:27:25.027 --> 00:27:26.860
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Baby sweetcorn.

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:27.575
Yeah.

00:27:27.575 --> 00:27:27.970
MARIANA SARACENI:
That's very random.

00:27:27.970 --> 00:27:28.675
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Yeah.

00:27:28.675 --> 00:27:30.716
MARIANA SARACENI: You
can't steal her answer, no.

00:27:30.716 --> 00:27:31.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:33.463
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Thank you

00:27:33.463 --> 00:27:34.520
for coming to my rescue.

00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:37.790
It's true that I can't get super
excited about baby sweetcorn.

00:27:37.790 --> 00:27:41.420
But even then, I don't hate it.

00:27:41.420 --> 00:27:42.140
I don't hate it.

00:27:45.530 --> 00:27:52.250
Actually, I find
bell peppers not

00:27:52.250 --> 00:27:57.136
super exciting on their own.

00:27:57.136 --> 00:27:58.760
There's a nice kind
of sweetness there,

00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:00.710
but I think they really
come into their own

00:28:00.710 --> 00:28:02.690
when they're roasted and
cooked and caramelized

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:04.490
and blended with other things.

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:08.090
And I always think that
thing of a salad that's

00:28:08.090 --> 00:28:14.480
got slices of green pepper and
slices of onion, of raw onion,

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:17.210
you've got harsh flavors
that aren't being

00:28:17.210 --> 00:28:20.710
sort of mollified or blended.

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:24.680
It's that salad that is
lettuce, cucumber, peppers,

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:26.210
and raw onions.

00:28:26.210 --> 00:28:29.630
It's like, those they're
all four great ingredients,

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:31.250
but they don't
necessarily just work

00:28:31.250 --> 00:28:33.170
if you plop them raw on
the side of the plate.

00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:34.340
MARIANA SARACENI: It's
like a plain salad.

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:36.299
Or you say, like something,
a plane that flies.

00:28:36.299 --> 00:28:38.464
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
I mean, I'd rather just

00:28:38.464 --> 00:28:41.060
have the lettuce with a nice
dressing or roast the peppers

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:42.950
and the onions
together or break them

00:28:42.950 --> 00:28:45.800
down really small
into a salsa so you've

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:49.490
got finely-chopped onion working
with a finely-chopped pepper.

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:53.152
And then maybe add some seeds
and spices and just kind of--

00:28:53.152 --> 00:28:54.110
MARIANA SARACENI: Yeah.

00:28:54.110 --> 00:28:55.370
I hear you.

00:28:55.370 --> 00:28:59.360
Bell peppers on their
own are impressive.

00:28:59.360 --> 00:29:02.180
For the next question, you
cannot say something like

00:29:02.180 --> 00:29:03.720
Italian.

00:29:03.720 --> 00:29:07.010
Three favorite
foods, items of food.

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:08.900
For example, I could
not live without them

00:29:08.900 --> 00:29:10.954
without tomatoes,
lemon, and rice.

00:29:10.954 --> 00:29:13.370
I would literally just give
up anything except those three

00:29:13.370 --> 00:29:13.897
things.

00:29:13.897 --> 00:29:15.230
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL: OK.

00:29:15.230 --> 00:29:17.060
This is really good that
you've got your mind made up

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:18.080
about this stuff.

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:18.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:18.760
MARIANA SARACENI:
Are you kidding me?

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:20.930
I have my death row meal
plan and everything.

00:29:20.930 --> 00:29:22.656
And I ask everybody
that I work with,

00:29:22.656 --> 00:29:23.780
even clients in interviews.

00:29:23.780 --> 00:29:26.360
The first thing I ask, before
we talk about anything, what

00:29:26.360 --> 00:29:27.787
are your three favorite foods?

00:29:27.787 --> 00:29:29.370
I need know what I'm
up against, guys.

00:29:31.364 --> 00:29:32.780
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Shall

00:29:32.780 --> 00:29:34.960
we say three
favorite vegetables?

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:37.664
MARIANA SARACENI: I leave
that poetic license to you.

00:29:37.664 --> 00:29:39.080
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
There

00:29:39.080 --> 00:29:44.750
are three things that
I think kind of we

00:29:44.750 --> 00:29:48.310
don't explore or do enough with.

00:29:48.310 --> 00:29:49.700
And I say one of
these as someone

00:29:49.700 --> 00:29:51.658
who used to be quite rude
about this vegetable,

00:29:51.658 --> 00:29:55.470
but I've really come
around to cauliflower.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:57.020
And I've come around
to it by virtue

00:29:57.020 --> 00:29:59.450
of doing things
like barbecuing it

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:02.030
or cutting it into thin
slices and putting it

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:04.550
in a really hot pan and getting
a little bit of color on it

00:30:04.550 --> 00:30:07.280
and then dressing it
with some oil and seeds.

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:10.640
Or, it makes a wonderful soup.

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:15.890
So cauliflower, let's talk
about the under-rated.

00:30:15.890 --> 00:30:18.650
Celeriac is another
one, which looks

00:30:18.650 --> 00:30:21.500
like a big, weird, curly
lump that you would struggle

00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:22.940
to get really
enthusiastic about,

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:25.480
but it's incredibly aromatic.

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:26.800
And it's got so many qualities.

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:27.970
And also, it's different.

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:30.550
If you shave it in very thin
slices, that's one thing.

00:30:30.550 --> 00:30:32.800
You can spread it
out and dress it raw.

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:34.250
Matchsticks raw is another.

00:30:34.250 --> 00:30:37.060
But then, cooked,
roasted again in cubes.

00:30:37.060 --> 00:30:39.250
Or, one of my
favorites, a mash of

00:30:39.250 --> 00:30:43.689
half celeriac and half potato
is really, really beautiful.

00:30:43.689 --> 00:30:45.480
MARIANA SARACENI: Jason
does it often here.

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:47.740
Seriously, it's like
a mash of things.

00:30:47.740 --> 00:30:49.440
Jason is our chef over there.

00:30:49.440 --> 00:30:53.205
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Or a celeriac gratin,

00:30:53.205 --> 00:30:55.610
thinly-sliced chilis.

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:57.940
Obviously, old school, you
would put a bit of cream in,

00:30:57.940 --> 00:31:01.040
but we don't necessarily
need to go there.

00:31:01.040 --> 00:31:02.770
I mean, that's the other thing.

00:31:02.770 --> 00:31:05.830
This book is vegan.

00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:08.260
It's not written
just for vegans.

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:10.100
It's written for everybody.

00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:15.310
And so the last veg book
was vegetarian but included

00:31:15.310 --> 00:31:17.670
cheese and dairy and all sorts.

00:31:17.670 --> 00:31:19.420
But I wanted to take
this to another level

00:31:19.420 --> 00:31:22.387
just really to prove the point
that I've been banging on about

00:31:22.387 --> 00:31:23.970
since I got here
really, which is just

00:31:23.970 --> 00:31:30.190
extraordinary under-explored
world of these vegetables

00:31:30.190 --> 00:31:33.460
where you don't need
the cheese on top.

00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:35.602
Of course, it's fine
and cool to put,

00:31:35.602 --> 00:31:37.060
and there's loads
of lovely recipes

00:31:37.060 --> 00:31:40.030
that combine vegetables with
dairy and vegetables with meat.

00:31:40.030 --> 00:31:44.500
But I just want to celebrate
vegetables in and of themselves

00:31:44.500 --> 00:31:47.440
and the amazing things
you can do with them.

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:49.300
Then, if you want to
add something on top

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:52.000
or put it on the side or
serve any of these recipes

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:56.350
next to a simply-cooked
piece of fish,

00:31:56.350 --> 00:31:57.770
I've got no problem with that.

00:31:57.770 --> 00:32:01.272
But right here, right now,
it's all about the veg.

00:32:01.272 --> 00:32:02.980
MARIANA SARACENI: To
be fair, we actually

00:32:02.980 --> 00:32:04.604
are very blessed here
at Google, and we

00:32:04.604 --> 00:32:06.580
have such a plethora of foods.

00:32:06.580 --> 00:32:09.130
The vegan days are
much, much easier

00:32:09.130 --> 00:32:11.710
because you guys give me
such great vegan options.

00:32:11.710 --> 00:32:12.490
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Because you have really

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:15.190
talented chefs here, and I've
met some of them already.

00:32:15.190 --> 00:32:16.810
And that's fantastic.

00:32:16.810 --> 00:32:21.010
For an organization
in their workplace

00:32:21.010 --> 00:32:22.960
to be able to offer
really seriously

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:26.080
well-thought-out
food that includes

00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:29.410
a really exciting attitude
to vegetables is very cool,

00:32:29.410 --> 00:32:31.000
but it is quite unusual.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.083
MARIANA SARACENI: It is
unusual, but I do love it.

