00:44:45.630 --> 00:44:49.320
and really bring out vegetables.

00:44:49.320 --> 00:44:51.120
It's kind of contrary
to a question asked

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:53.700
before where you were like,
which cuisine inspires you

00:44:53.700 --> 00:44:55.530
the most, but are
there any cuisines

00:44:55.530 --> 00:44:59.690
you found which are really
difficult to create veg

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:01.950
recipes from but that
you've kind of managed

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:04.627
to find inspiration from?

00:45:04.627 --> 00:45:06.210
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Any areas

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:07.470
that are difficult to create?

00:45:07.470 --> 00:45:09.980
AUDIENCE: Any cuisines
which are not veg-focused?

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:11.480
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
I think

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:17.490
sort of Central European cooking
and old school British-English

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:20.160
cooking is not massively
adventurous with veg.

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:21.730
We have to face up to that.

00:45:21.730 --> 00:45:25.960
And as soon as you get around
to other parts of the world--

00:45:25.960 --> 00:45:29.484
I mean, I suppose it's
partly a climate thing,

00:45:29.484 --> 00:45:31.650
but I don't think that's a
good enough excuse for us

00:45:31.650 --> 00:45:33.149
because we know
that in this country

00:45:33.149 --> 00:45:35.550
we can grow
wonderful vegetables.

00:45:35.550 --> 00:45:39.060
But it's also a
cultural thing where

00:45:39.060 --> 00:45:42.300
to be putting meat
on the table seemed

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:45.120
like a kind of priority,
a kind of way of saying,

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:46.600
we're doing OK.

00:45:46.600 --> 00:45:48.210
Look, we've got meat every day.

00:45:48.210 --> 00:45:50.670
And I think that's what
drove a lot of the idea

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:53.430
that everyone could have
a chicken in the oven

00:45:53.430 --> 00:45:55.200
every weekend.

00:45:55.200 --> 00:45:56.040
That's one thing.

00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:58.890
But a chicken in a
sandwich every day

00:45:58.890 --> 00:46:02.040
or a piece of fried
chicken in a bun every day,

00:46:02.040 --> 00:46:04.810
that's led to industrial
farming, and that's

00:46:04.810 --> 00:46:06.100
a whole different thing.

00:46:06.100 --> 00:46:12.930
But I think that the tropical
cuisines of the world

00:46:12.930 --> 00:46:18.090
and also, often, the peasant
cuisines of the world

00:46:18.090 --> 00:46:21.930
are much more resourceful
with vegetables.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:24.540
And so all over Asia,
but also South America,

00:46:24.540 --> 00:46:28.830
you've got great traditions
of using things like beans

00:46:28.830 --> 00:46:32.100
and rice as the essential
food and then jazzing them up

00:46:32.100 --> 00:46:33.990
with all kinds of
delicious vegetables

00:46:33.990 --> 00:46:38.790
and fruit and spices
and nuts coming into it.

00:46:38.790 --> 00:46:41.400
But, I mean, we should all
have that vernacular now.

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:46.030
And I'm sure there's all kinds
of influences in those recipes

00:46:46.030 --> 00:46:47.910
which I could start
to deconstruct,

00:46:47.910 --> 00:46:49.610
but I wouldn't even
be conscious of them

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:51.180
when I put the recipe together.

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:53.820
But definitely, a lot of Indian
and Asian in there, and I

00:46:53.820 --> 00:46:55.500
guess some Mexican
and South American

00:46:55.500 --> 00:46:59.978
stuff, a lot of good ideas
around veg come from there.

00:46:59.978 --> 00:47:01.824
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:01.824 --> 00:47:02.990
MARIANA SARACENI: Go for it.

00:47:02.990 --> 00:47:04.200
If it's quick, you can come in.

00:47:04.200 --> 00:47:04.500
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:05.020
Thank you.

00:47:05.020 --> 00:47:05.728
Nice to meet you.

00:47:05.728 --> 00:47:08.040
Thank you very
much for your time.

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:11.160
We've seen the advent of
the impossible burger.

00:47:11.160 --> 00:47:14.280
And given that agribusinesses is
the single largest contributor

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:16.560
to greenhouse gases
on the planet--

00:47:16.560 --> 00:47:20.429
so basically it's warming the
planet through cows farting--

00:47:20.429 --> 00:47:22.470
with the advent of the
impossible burger and meat

00:47:22.470 --> 00:47:25.410
being made from plants,
what's your take

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:29.484
or how does this kind
of resonate with you?

00:47:29.484 --> 00:47:30.900
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Look.

00:47:30.900 --> 00:47:34.740
I mean, creating meat-like
textures from plants

00:47:34.740 --> 00:47:39.120
probably is not a bad idea
because so many people are

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:41.370
attached to those
consistencies and flavors.

00:47:41.370 --> 00:47:46.410
I haven't done the taste test
for that so-called thing.

00:47:49.290 --> 00:47:53.490
I don't think it's
necessarily central.

00:47:53.490 --> 00:47:56.610
I think really being
much more relaxed

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:59.100
without denaturing them
or reconstructing them

00:47:59.100 --> 00:48:01.340
or growing strange
things in laboratories,

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:05.310
vegetables already offer
us a massive solution

00:48:05.310 --> 00:48:08.290
to the problems of
global agriculture.

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:10.680
But the thing we
mustn't forget--

00:48:10.680 --> 00:48:14.880
and it's so easy to-- is that
ultimately it is our choice.

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:17.430
And I get that huge
amounts of money

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:21.030
are spent on us making
the choices that industry

00:48:21.030 --> 00:48:21.970
wants to make.

00:48:21.970 --> 00:48:25.410
And that's not like some
big sinister conspiracy.

00:48:25.410 --> 00:48:26.790
That's just capitalism.

00:48:26.790 --> 00:48:29.430
That's just the drive
of making money.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:32.010
And it's all about margins
and people have found out,

00:48:32.010 --> 00:48:36.840
as I said at the beginning, that
cheap starch, fat, and sugar--

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:39.090
all highly-refined fats
and carbohydrates--

00:48:39.090 --> 00:48:41.850
can be whizzed into
any number of things.

00:48:41.850 --> 00:48:44.430
Somehow, we have to
push back against that

00:48:44.430 --> 00:48:46.890
by knowing what's really good
for us and for the planet

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:49.555
and making the choices that
are going to make a difference.

00:48:49.555 --> 00:48:50.890
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:50.890 --> 00:48:52.320
HUGH FEARNLEY-WHITTINGSTALL:
Thank you very much.

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:53.010
MARIANA SARACENI:
Our last question

00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:54.270
